			data: "WEBVTT\n\n00:00.232 --> 00:04.968\nAFP surveillance can be broken down into five major steps\n\n00:05.295 --> 00:09.487\nAll these steps and activities are time sensitive\n\n00:10.216 --> 00:21.640\nThis is important because the sooner we identify a case of polio the quicker we can respond to the outbreak\n\n00:23.752 --> 00:41.992\nThe first step is the onset of paralysis to notification it is the most important step of the whole process as that’s when a health staff or a community informant detect a potential case of polio and informs the surveillance system.\n\n00:42.280 --> 00:54.248\nAs is shown in this graph notification of AFP case should happen at most within seven days of the onset of paralysis\n\n00:54.312 --> 00:57.928\nIn fact, all AFP cases must be identified and notified as quickly as possible.\n\n01:00.104 --> 01:04.424\nThe second step in the process is the investigation of the AFP case\n\n01:04.776 --> 01:17.608\nThis is when we know there is a potential case and we do a thorough interview and clinical examination of the case to collect all clinical information it should happen rapidly within 48 hours of the notification\n\n01:18.212 --> 01:23.556\nThe third step is when we collect stool specimens from the AFP case\n\n01:24.296 --> 01:40.680\nWe need to collect two stool specimens as soon as possible and within one day of the case investigation then comes the fourth step, which is the testing of the stool specimens in a WHO accredited laboratories\n\n01:40.781 --> 01:48.205\nThis is when we know for sure whether the paralysis is caused\n by the polio virus or not\n\n01:49.697 --> 02:05.057\nThe fifth set of activities is the follow up examination of the AFP case 60 days after the onset of paralysis and the review AFP cases by the countries expert review committee\n\n02:05.549 --> 02:12.365\nGo into the details of steps and activities 2 to 5 in later modules in this module\n\n02:12.863 --> 02:21.343\nWe will focus on the first step onset of paralysis to notification.\n\n"
